<DOC><DOCNO> AP881003-0278 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 0907EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History ADV15   10-03 0478</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, ADV15,0495</SECOND><NOTE>$adv15^For Release Saturday, Oct. 15</NOTE><HEAD>Today in History</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Today is Saturday, Oct. 15, the 289th day of 1988. There are 77days left in the year.   Today's highlight in history:   On Oct. 15, 1860, 11-year-old Grace Bedell of Westfield, N.Y.,wrote a letter to presidential candidate Abraham Lincoln suggestinghe would look better if he were to grow a beard.   On this date:   In 1914, the Clayton Antitrust Act was passed.   In 1917, Mata Hari, a Dutch dancer who had spied for theGermans, was executed by firing squad outside Paris.   In 1928, the German dirigible ``Graf Zeppelin'' landed inLakehurst, N.J., on its first commercial flight across the Atlantic.   In 1937, the Ernest Hemingway novel ``To Have and Have Not'' wasfirst published.   In 1945, the former premier of Vichy France, Pierre Laval, wasexecuted.   In 1946, Nazi war criminal Hermann Goering poisoned himself oneday before he was to be executed.   In 1951, the television series ``I Love Lucy,'' starring LucilleBall and Desi Arnaz, premiered on CBS.   In 1964, it was announced that Soviet leader Nikita S.Khrushchev had been removed from office. He was succeeded aspremier by Alexei N. Kosygin and as Communist Party secretary byLeonid I. Brezhnev.   In 1966, President Lyndon B. Johnson signed a bill creating theDepartment of Transportation.   In 1969, peace demonstrators staged activities across thecountry, including a candlelight march around the White House, aspart of a moratorium against the Vietnam War.   In 1976, in the first debate of its kind, the major-ticketvice-presidential nominees, Democrat Walter Mondale and RepublicanBob Dole, faced off in Houston.   Ten years ago: The 95th Congress adjourned after an all-nightsession during which lawmakers took final action on about two dozenbills, including energy legislation, tax reduction, airlinederegulation and the Humphrey-Hawkins full-employment measure.   Five years ago: U.S. Marine sharpshooters reported killing fivesnipers who had pinned them down at Beirut International Airport _the first time since the Marines were deployed in Lebanon that theyreported killing combatants.   One year ago: Frantic rescue efforts continued in Midland,Texas, to save 18-month-old Jessica McClure, who had fallen 22 feetdown an abandoned well the day before. (Jessica was freed thefollowing evening.)   Today's birthdays: Economist John Kenneth Galbraith is 80.Author and historian Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr. is 71. Author MarioPuzo is 68. Chrysler chairman Lee Iacocca is 64. Actress LindaLavin is 51. Actress-director Penny Marshall is 43. MusicianRichard Carpenter is 42. Tennis player Roscoe Tanner is 37. SingerTito Jackson is 35. Britain's Duchess of York (formerly SarahFerguson) is 29.   Thought for today: ``The young do not know enough to be prudent,and therefore they attempt the impossible _ and achieve it,generation after generation.'' _ Pearl S. Buck, American Pulitzerand Nobel Prize-winning author (1892-1973).</TEXT></DOC>